inst:effect_3010 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3010" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3011 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasEffectSizeValue "15.78"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3012 ;
    evid:hasIndividualSampleSize "42.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasNotes "Concomitancy: communication variable should change as training segment (briefing, scenario, debriefing) is varied. To determine whether LSA communication metrics were similarly affected, we computed mean vector length (semantic content) across utterances for each team at each training segment and analyzed those values using a 3 (training Segment) × 2 (Experience) mixed ANOVA. All ANOVA assumptions were tested and upheld. As with neurodynamic entropy, only the training segment effect was significant, F(2, 10) = 15.78, p < .001, η2 = .76. A Tukey test on training segment (αFW = .05) similarly revealed that vector lengths were significantly different during debriefing compared to briefing and scenario (Figure 3b). This result indicates that communication content was terser and domain specific during briefing and scenario and lengthier and domain specific during debriefing.; 2 segments looked at: briefing & scenario and debriefing. Together, these results suggest that training segments (briefing, scenario) that lead to a more flexible team neurophysiological distribution (higher entropy) also resulted in terser domain- specific communication (smaller vector lengths), which we take as evidence for concomitancy."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasPValue "0.001"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasTeamSampleSize "7.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:perturbationPhase "Training segment"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "F-test / ANOVA"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3011 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3011" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3011 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasEffectSizeValue "19.77"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3013 ;
    evid:hasIndividualSampleSize "42.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasNotes "Concomitancy: neural variable should change as training segment (briefing, scenario, debriefing) is varied. To examine the effects of training segment and experience on neurodynamic entropy, we computed mean entropy for each team at each training segment and analyzed those values using a 3 (training segment) × 2 (experience) mixed ANOVA. All ANOVA assumptions were tested and upheld. Only the training segment effect was significant, F(2, 10) = 19.77, p < .001, η2 = .80. A Tukey test on training segment (αFW = .05) revealed that debriefing entropy was significantly lower than either briefing or scenario entropy. This result indicates that the neurophysiological distribution across team members was more flexible during briefing and scenario but more fixed during debriefing.; 2 segments looked at: briefing & scenario and debriefing. Together, these results suggest that training segments (briefing, scenario) that lead to a more flexible team neurophysiological distribution (higher entropy) also resulted in terser domain- specific communication (smaller vector lengths), which we take as evidence for concomitancy."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasPValue "0.001"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasTeamSampleSize "7.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:perturbationPhase "Training segment"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "F-test / ANOVA"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3012 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3012" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3011 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasEffectSizeValue "0.86"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3012 ;
    evid:hasIndividualSampleSize "42.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasNotes "Mutual Discrimination: neural and communication variables_x000D_ should mutually discriminate between more and less experienced teams.; The two-dimensional MDS solution (Stress = .86; R2 =.96) similarly revealed that more and less experienced teams were positioned at opposite ends of an “experience” dimension (Figure 4b). The second MDS dimension discriminated teams along an as-yet-unidentified factor. Together, these results indicate that semantic similarity and neurodynamic entropy both discriminate between more and less experienced teams (mutual discrimination).because mutual discrimination was specific only to the scenario segment, it suggests that mutual discrimination may be specific to more dynamic, real-time aspects of team performance, such as scenario performance."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasTeamSampleSize "7.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:perturbationPhase "briefing, scenario, and debriefing"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "multidimensional scaling (MDS): Stress"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3013 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3013" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3011 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasEffectSizeValue "7.61"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3013 ;
    evid:hasIndividualSampleSize "42.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasNotes "Mutual Discrimination: neural and communication variables_x000D_ should mutually discriminate between more and less experienced teams. Discriminant Function Analysis (also called Discriminant Analysis). This analysis determines whether neural measures (entropy) can successfully classify teams into \"more experienced\" vs \"less experienced\" groups. Classification/Discrimination effect - testing whether the neural variables can distinguish between the two experience groups.; Λ = .15, χ2(2) = 7.61, p = .022, ϕ2 = .54. Together, these results indicate that semantic similarity and neurodynamic entropy both discriminate between more and less experienced teams (mutual discrimination).because mutual discrimination was specific only to the scenario segment, it suggests that mutual discrimination may be specific to more dynamic, real-time aspects of team performance, such as scenario performance."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasPValue "0.022"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasTeamSampleSize "7.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:perturbationPhase "briefing, scenario, and debriefing"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "chi-square"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3014 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3014" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3012 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3013 ;
    evid:hasIndividualSampleSize "42.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasNotes "Cross-Correlations: Our third research question was whether the development of cross-level effects can be observed through differences in lead-lag cross-correlations between neural and communication variables across more and less experienced teams. We calculated lagged cross-correlation functions between LSA vector length of each utterance (Variable 1) and mean entropy during each utterance (Variable 2) for each transcript using the MatLab crosscorr function; Lead-lag analysis examining temporal coupling between neural flexibility and communication efficiency. Negative correlations suggest higher neural entropy precedes shorter/more efficient communication. Not seeing an r-statistic here."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasTeamSampleSize "7.0"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:perturbationPhase "training segment"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "Peak cross-correlation values (they report 14 of 19 were significant and negative)"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3015 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3015" ;
    evid:hasDependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3014 ;
    evid:hasEffectLevel "team"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasEffectSizeValue "0.256"^^xsd:float ;
    evid:hasIndependentVariable inst:measure_meas_3022 ;
    evid:hasNotes "false alarm rates in the medium condition were higher if the Lyapunov exponent was also higher (r = .256, p < .05); more errors were associated with greater turbulence in the target person’s arousal levels."^^xsd:string ;
    evid:hasSignificanceCategory "Significantly positive"^^xsd:string ;
    evid:usesEffectSizeMetric "Pearson r"^^xsd:string .

inst:effect_3016 a evid:EffectSize ;
    rdfs:label "effect_3016" ;
