inst:measure_meas_039 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """Team membersâ€™ contri-
butions were segmented into conversational moves cor-
responding to Hirokawaâ€™s (19) definition of a functional
utterance. That is, a unit was an uninterrupted utter-
ance by a team member that had a discrete problem-
solving function. As such, a unit could correspond to a
grammatical sentence, to an independent clause, or to
several sentences. For each unit we noted its grammat-
ical form (declarative, interrogative, imperative, or el-
lipsis) and speaker. The task-related (i.e., problem-solv-
ing) function of a unit was classified using the coding
scheme developed by Orasanu and Fischer (35). Main
and sub-categories plus examples are provided in Ta-
ble I.""",
        "Team members’ contri-_x000D_ butions were segmented into conversational moves cor-_x000D_ responding to Hirokawa’s (19) definition of a functional_x000D_ utterance. That is, a unit was an uninterrupted utter-_x000D_ ance by a team member that had a discrete problem-_x000D_ solving function. As such, a unit could correspond to a_x000D_ grammatical sentence, to an independent clause, or to_x000D_ several sentences. For each unit we noted its grammat-_x000D_ ical form (declarative, interrogative, imperative, or el-_x000D_ lipsis) and speaker. The task-related (i.e., problem-solv-_x000D_ ing) function of a unit was classified using the coding_x000D_ scheme developed by Orasanu and Fischer (35). Main_x000D_ and sub-categories plus examples are provided in Ta-_x000D_ ble I." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "See table 1" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasScale "The task-related (i.e., problem-solv-_x000D_ ing) function of a unit was classified using the coding_x000D_ scheme developed by Orasanu and Fischer (35" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_content ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_task_outcome ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_language_analysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_analysis_human_coding,
        inst:tech_language_anlaysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_anlaysis_human_coding .

inst:measure_meas_040 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """Our analyses focused on the
control structure and interactive patterns in teams, as
well as on team membersâ€™ identification with and affec-
tive responses to the group. Several LIWC categories
were exploited for our purposes. The word count cate-
gory was applied to assess how much each team mem-
ber talked and whether an individual or individuals
talked more than others, thus dominating the teamâ€™s
discourse. In addition, we used the LIWC to count how
often team members referred to themselves (frequency
of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., â€œIâ€) or to the
team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,
â€œweâ€) and how often positive or negative emotion
words occurred in their communications. The former
categories were expected to tap team membersâ€™ identi-
fication with the group; the latter to gauge the social
climate in a team. These LIWC categories were complemented by hand-
coding team membersâ€™ communications for expressions
of specific interpersonal affect. Our affect codes were
modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used
to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28).
We coded whether or not speakers verbalized affective reactions to teammates, and when they did we further
noted whether they expressed praise and empathy,
showed humor or politeness, or tried to appease, or
were apologetic, patronizing, criticizing, or defensive
(see Table II for a listing of the categories and exam-
ples).""",
        "Our analyses focused on the_x000D_ control structure and interactive patterns in teams, as_x000D_ well as on team members’ identification with and affec-_x000D_ tive responses to the group. Several LIWC categories_x000D_ were exploited for our purposes. The word count cate-_x000D_ gory was applied to assess how much each team mem-_x000D_ ber talked and whether an individual or individuals_x000D_ talked more than others, thus dominating the team’s_x000D_ discourse. In addition, we used the LIWC to count how_x000D_ often team members referred to themselves (frequency_x000D_ of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., “I”) or to the_x000D_ team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,_x000D_ “we”) and how often positive or negative emotion_x000D_ words occurred in their communications. The former_x000D_ categories were expected to tap team members’ identi-_x000D_ fication with the group; the latter to gauge the social_x000D_ climate in a team. These LIWC categories were complemented by hand-_x000D_ coding team members’ communications for expressions_x000D_ of specific interpersonal affect. Our affect codes were_x000D_ modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used_x000D_ to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28)._x000D_ We coded whether or not speakers verbalized affective reactions to teammates, and when they did we further_x000D_ noted whether they expressed praise and empathy,_x000D_ showed humor or politeness, or tried to appease, or_x000D_ were apologetic, patronizing, criticizing, or defensive_x000D_ (see Table II for a listing of the categories and exam-_x000D_ ples)." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "See talble 2" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasScale "Our affect codes were_x000D_ modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used_x000D_ to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28)." ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_content ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_interpersonal_team_process,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_language_analysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_analysis_human_coding,
        inst:tech_language_anlaysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_anlaysis_human_coding .

inst:measure_meas_041 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """Our analyses focused on the
control structure and interactive patterns in teams, as
well as on team membersâ€™ identification with and affec-
tive responses to the group. Several LIWC categories
were exploited for our purposes. The word count cate-
gory was applied to assess how much each team mem-
ber talked and whether an individual or individuals
talked more than others, thus dominating the teamâ€™s
discourse. In addition, we used the LIWC to count how
often team members referred to themselves (frequency
of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., â€œIâ€) or to the
team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,
â€œweâ€) and how often positive or negative emotion
words occurred in their communications. The former
categories were expected to tap team membersâ€™ identi-
fication with the group; the latter to gauge the social
climate in a team. These LIWC categories were complemented by hand-
coding team membersâ€™ communications for expressions
of specific interpersonal affect. Our affect codes were
modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used
to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28).
We coded whether or not speakers verbalized affective reactions to teammates, and when they did we further
noted whether they expressed praise and empathy,
showed humor or politeness, or tried to appease, or
were apologetic, patronizing, criticizing, or defensive
(see Table II for a listing of the categories and exam-
ples).""",
        "Our analyses focused on the_x000D_ control structure and interactive patterns in teams, as_x000D_ well as on team members’ identification with and affec-_x000D_ tive responses to the group. Several LIWC categories_x000D_ were exploited for our purposes. The word count cate-_x000D_ gory was applied to assess how much each team mem-_x000D_ ber talked and whether an individual or individuals_x000D_ talked more than others, thus dominating the team’s_x000D_ discourse. In addition, we used the LIWC to count how_x000D_ often team members referred to themselves (frequency_x000D_ of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., “I”) or to the_x000D_ team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,_x000D_ “we”) and how often positive or negative emotion_x000D_ words occurred in their communications. The former_x000D_ categories were expected to tap team members’ identi-_x000D_ fication with the group; the latter to gauge the social_x000D_ climate in a team. These LIWC categories were complemented by hand-_x000D_ coding team members’ communications for expressions_x000D_ of specific interpersonal affect. Our affect codes were_x000D_ modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used_x000D_ to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28)._x000D_ We coded whether or not speakers verbalized affective reactions to teammates, and when they did we further_x000D_ noted whether they expressed praise and empathy,_x000D_ showed humor or politeness, or tried to appease, or_x000D_ were apologetic, patronizing, criticizing, or defensive_x000D_ (see Table II for a listing of the categories and exam-_x000D_ ples)." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "See talble 2" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasScale "Our affect codes were_x000D_ modeled after coding schemes psychologists have used_x000D_ to classify speaker affect in marital interaction (14,28)." ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_content ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_interpersonal_team_process,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_language_analysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_analysis_human_coding,
        inst:tech_language_anlaysis_closed_vocabulary_liwc_language_anlaysis_human_coding .

inst:measure_meas_042 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription "For each scenario we computed the standard deviation of team membersâ€™ word count as a measure of variability in team membersâ€™ amount of talk and thus as an indication of their differential influence on their teamâ€™s interaction. We then correlated this measurement with the teamâ€™s corresponding performance score (i.e., point total) to determine whether team success was related to a particular control structure. ",
        "For each scenario we computed the standard deviation of team members’ word count as a measure of variability in team members’ amount of talk and thus as an indication of their differential influence on their team’s interaction. We then correlated this measurement with the team’s corresponding performance score (i.e., point total) to determine whether team success was related to a particular control structure." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Difference in score suggesting that in_x000D_ unsuccessful teams one or several team members dom-_x000D_ inated the discourse, while talk and, thus, control were_x000D_ more equally distributed among team members of suc-_x000D_ cessful teams." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_flow ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_communication,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation_dispersion .

inst:measure_meas_043 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """Analyses of the communication flow between team
members in successful and unsuccessful teams lend
further support to this interpretation. For each team
member, we noted how often the other three team
members responded to his contributions during a sce-
nario, and summarized the resulting pattern in a flow
diagram. We focused on team membersâ€™ responses
rather than on their initiations to characterize their in-
teractive behavior because team members tended to
broadcast their communications for everybody to hear,
frequently without identifying a specific addressee. The
communication flow typical of unsuccessful teams is
represented in the right portion of Fig. 2. """,
        "Analyses of the communication flow between team_x000D_ members in successful and unsuccessful teams lend_x000D_ further support to this interpretation. For each team_x000D_ member, we noted how often the other three team_x000D_ members responded to his contributions during a sce-_x000D_ nario, and summarized the resulting pattern in a flow_x000D_ diagram. We focused on team members’ responses_x000D_ rather than on their initiations to characterize their in-_x000D_ teractive behavior because team members tended to_x000D_ broadcast their communications for everybody to hear,_x000D_ frequently without identifying a specific addressee. The_x000D_ communication flow typical of unsuccessful teams is_x000D_ represented in the right portion of Fig. 2." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "See fig 2; indicating that balanced and inclusive rela-_x000D_ tionships were associated with higher performance." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasScale "Scores could range from 0, indicating no vari-_x000D_ ance in team members’ interactive relations and, thus, a_x000D_ well integrated team, to 1," ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_flow ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_team_affect,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation_sequence_counts .

inst:measure_meas_044 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """In addition, we used the LIWC to count how
often team members referred to themselves (frequency
of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., â€œIâ€) or to the
team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,
â€œweâ€) """,
        "In addition, we used the LIWC to count how_x000D_ often team members referred to themselves (frequency_x000D_ of first-person singular pronouns, e.g., “I”) or to the_x000D_ team (frequency of first-person plural pronouns, e.g.,_x000D_ “we”)" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_flow ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_team_affect,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_language_analysis_closed_vocabulary_pronoun_use,
        inst:tech_language_anlaysis_closed_vocabulary_pronoun_use .

inst:measure_meas_045 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "LIWC" ;
    meas:hasDescription """Interactive patterns also reflect how well team mem-
bers collaborate with one another and get along (42,43).
On a relational level, collaboration concerns the extent
to which team members are responsive to one another,
take up and extend each otherâ€™s contributions, and
build consensus. Moreover, the frequency of team
membersâ€™ agreement relative to their disagreement car-
ries affective meaning insofar as agreements are consid-
ered to be positive conversational moves while dis-
agreements are judged to be negative. Consequently, a
preponderance of agreement is believed to indicate a
positive team climate, which, in turn, is assumed nec-
essary for team success (1).""",
        "Interactive patterns also reflect how well team mem-_x000D_ bers collaborate with one another and get along (42,43)._x000D_ On a relational level, collaboration concerns the extent_x000D_ to which team members are responsive to one another,_x000D_ take up and extend each other’s contributions, and_x000D_ build consensus. Moreover, the frequency of team_x000D_ members’ agreement relative to their disagreement car-_x000D_ ries affective meaning insofar as agreements are consid-_x000D_ ered to be positive conversational moves while dis-_x000D_ agreements are judged to be negative. Consequently, a_x000D_ preponderance of agreement is believed to indicate a_x000D_ positive team climate, which, in turn, is assumed nec-_x000D_ essary for team success (1)." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "See Table 3;" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "LIWC" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_communication_flow ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_coordination,
        inst:construct_team_cohesion ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation_percentage .

inst:measure_meas_049 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Team Performance" ;
    meas:hasDescription """based on the
number of trees ( 1 point) and houses
( 50 points) destroyed by the fire. Points began at
100% of the possible points in the scenario and
were deducted based on the number of trees and
houses burned during the scenario """,
        "based on the_x000D_ number of trees ( 1 point) and houses_x000D_ ( 50 points) destroyed by the fire. Points began at_x000D_ 100% of the possible points in the scenario and_x000D_ were deducted based on the number of trees and_x000D_ houses burned during the scenario" ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Higher numbe/percentage, better score" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_team ;
    meas:hasName "Team Performance" ;
    meas:hasScale "0-100%" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_task_outcome ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_task_outcome ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation_sum .

