inst:measure_meas_3021 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Synchronization Weight (non linear model)" ;
    meas:hasDescription "The synchronization weight in the nonlinear model quantifies how much one participant’s physiological dynamics are influenced by their partner’s, allowing for complex, nonlinear relationships (e.g., thresholds, amplification, or dampening effects)." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Higher values is stronger coupling, lower values is weak coupling" ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "Synchronization Weight (non linear model)" ;
    meas:hasScale "continuous" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_physiological ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_adaptation ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_nonlinear_dynamical_systems_modeling .

inst:measure_meas_3022 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Lyapunov Exponent" ;
    meas:hasDescription "The Lyapunov Exponent (LE) is a nonlinear dynamical systems measure that quantifies the degree of stability or chaos in a time series—in this case, participants’ physiological signals (e.g., electrodermal activity/GSR). It reflects how quickly nearby states in the system diverge over time, indicating whether the system is stable or unpredictable." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Higher exponent indicates greater instability, lower exponent indicates greater stability." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "Lyapunov Exponent" ;
    meas:hasScale "Continous (negative, near zero, positive)" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_physiological ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_physiological_synchrony ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_nonlinear_time_series_analysis_dynamical_systems_modeling .

inst:measure_meas_3026 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "TLX" ;
    meas:hasDescription "TLX Session 2. Participants completed the TLX ratings with a 21-point rating scale (Hart & Staveland, 1988; NASA, n.d.). TLX has a long history of use as a set of subjective ratings of workload.The six ratings were mental demand, physical demand, temporal demand (time pressure), performance, effort, and frustration." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Higher TLX scores indicate greater perceived workload." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "TLX" ;
    meas:hasScale "Scales were anchored as 1 = “very low” and 21 = “very high.”" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_self_report ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_workload ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation .

inst:measure_meas_3027 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "TLX" ;
    meas:hasDescription "TLX Session 3. Participants completed the TLX ratings with a 21-point rating scale (Hart & Staveland, 1988; NASA, n.d.). TLX has a long history of use as a set of subjective ratings of workload. The six ratings were mental demand, physical demand, temporal demand (time pressure), performance, effort, and frustration." ;
    meas:hasInterpretation "Higher TLX scores indicate greater perceived workload." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "TLX" ;
    meas:hasScale "Scales were anchored as 1 = “very low” and 21 = “very high.”" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_self_report ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_workload ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation .

inst:measure_meas_3028 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Leadership" ;
    meas:hasDescription "Leadership Session 2. Participants completed a brief questionnaire at the end of the third game of each session that asked who was most like the leader and second most like the leader. Participants who were designated as most like the leader by a particular participant received a score of 2, and those who were designated as second most like the leader were given a score of 1. (In other words, the respondents’ desig_x0002_nations of 1 and 2 were reversed for scoring purposes.) All others received a score of 0." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "Leadership" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_team_rating ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_leadership ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation .

inst:measure_meas_3029 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Leadership" ;
    meas:hasDescription "Leadership Session 3. Participants completed a brief questionnaire at the end of the third game of each session that asked who was most like the leader and second most like the leader. Participants who were designated as most like the leader by a particular participant received a score of 2, and those who were designated as second most like the leader were given a score of 1. (In other words, the respondents’ desig_x0002_nations of 1 and 2 were reversed for scoring purposes.) All others received a score of 0." ;
    meas:hasLevelOfAnalysis inst:level_individual_level ;
    meas:hasName "Leadership" ;
    meas:includesModality inst:modality_team_rating ;
    meas:measuresConstruct inst:construct_leadership ;
    meas:usesAnalyticTechnique inst:tech_simple_aggregation .

inst:measure_meas_3030 a meas:Measure ;
    rdfs:label "Emotional Intelligence" ;
    meas:hasDescription "In addition to the points that were already made concerning drivers, empaths, TLX ratings, and what said individuals do while solving problems, one last set of analyses were conducted to ascertain the relationship between drivers and empaths, as determined by the 0-6 scales, and their self-ratings of emotional intelligence, anxiety, and empathy." ;
